# Civic Platform Development Rules

## Code Style
- Use TypeScript for all new code
- Follow NestJS best practices for backend
- Follow Next.js 14 App Router patterns for frontend
- Use functional components with hooks
- Prefer composition over inheritance

## File Naming
- Components: PascalCase (e.g., `UserProfile.tsx`)
- Utilities: camelCase (e.g., `formatDate.ts`)
- Constants: UPPER_SNAKE_CASE (e.g., `API_BASE_URL.ts`)
- Types: PascalCase with `.types.ts` suffix (e.g., `user.types.ts`)

## Project Structure
- Keep modules self-contained
- Share code through `packages/shared`
- Use feature-based folder structure
- Separate concerns (UI, logic, data)

## GraphQL
- Use descriptive query/mutation names
- Include all necessary fields
- Handle errors gracefully
- Use fragments for reusable fields

## Database
- All queries must be tenant-scoped
- Use Prisma for all database operations
- Add indexes for frequently queried fields
- Use transactions for multi-step operations

## Security
- Never expose sensitive data in logs
- Validate all user inputs
- Use parameterized queries (Prisma handles this)
- Check permissions before operations
- Log security-relevant events

## Testing
- Write tests for critical paths
- Test error cases
- Mock external dependencies
- Keep tests simple and focused

## Documentation
- Document complex logic
- Add JSDoc comments for public APIs
- Keep README files updated
- Document API changes

## Git Workflow
- Use descriptive commit messages
- Create feature branches
- Review code before merging
- Keep commits focused and atomic

## Performance
- Optimize database queries
- Use pagination for lists
- Cache when appropriate
- Monitor query performance

## Error Handling
- Provide user-friendly error messages
- Log errors with context
- Handle edge cases
- Fail gracefully
